document.title: District of Columbia Arts Education Learning Standards

F83D15D0DFE40131639268A86D17958E.description: Recognize American symbols (flag colors and shapes, monuments, the statue of Liberty) and symbols used in commercial products created by artists and designers that can be seen at an art museum such as the Corcoran Gallery of Art.

F83C94D0DFE40131639168A86D17958E.description: Identify art forms (e.g., photographs, paintings, murals, ceramics, sculptures) and images found at home, in school, and in the community.

F83BC720DFE40131638F68A86D17958E.description: Look at and draw something used every day (e.g., scissors, toothbrush, fork) and describe how the object is used.

F83B5170DFE40131638E68A86D17958E.description: Draw geometric shapes (e.g., circles, squares, triangles) and repeat them in dance/movement sequences.

F83ADF40DFE40131638D68A86D17958E.description: Draw lines (e.g., curved, straight, parallel) to represent movements used in play.

F83A14B0DFE40131638B68A86D17958E.description: Connect and apply what is learned in the visual arts to other art forms, subject areas, visual culture and communications and to careers. (Connections, Relationships, Applications)

F839B240DFE40131638A68A86D17958E.description: Describe various reasons that he/she has made art in the way that it was done.

F8394730DFE40131638968A86D17958E.description: Discuss how and why students made a specific work of art and provide reasons why they like it, using appropriate art vocabulary.

F838D300DFE40131638868A86D17958E.description: Discuss subject of the work and how it relates to the color, shape, form, and texture.

F8386140DFE40131638768A86D17958E.description: Discuss the objects in own works of art, using appropriate art vocabulary (e.g., color, shape, form, texture. Student holds art and says, "This is my mommy wearing a yellow color and me wearing blue stripes).

F8379130DFE40131638568A86D17958E.description: Respond to, analyze, and make judgments about works in the visual arts. (Aesthetics, Valuing & Perspectives of Art)

F8372530DFE40131638468A86D17958E.description: Identify, describe, and discuss the meaning of visual elements and symbols of holidays, birthdays, and/or cultural events (e.g. birthday candles, pi√±atas, menorahs).

F836AE20DFE40131638368A86D17958E.description: Identify and describe works of art that show people working and living together (genre paintings or sculpture).

F8363440DFE40131638268A86D17958E.description: Investigate everyday objects from various time periods and cultures by comparing and contrasting them with objects students recognize from their daily lives (e.g. ceramic mug from US and ceramic tea bowl from Japan).

F835C3A0DFE40131638168A86D17958E.description: Recognize, describe, and discuss American and international flags and symbols.

F8355C00DFE40131638068A86D17958E.description: Describe functional and non-utilitarian art seen in daily life, (e.g., works of art that are used versus those that are for viewing).

F834E280DFE40131637F68A86D17958E.description: Historical Development, Role and Cultural Diversity of the Visual Arts

F8348150DFE40131637E68A86D17958E.description: Investigate and understand historical and cultural dimensions of the visual arts and to construct meaning in the diverse ways in which human experience is expressed across time and place. (Historical and Cultural Context)

F8341FA0DFE40131637D68A86D17958E.description: Create three-dimensional forms (e.g., a real or imaginary animal) using clay and other workable media.

F833B8F0DFE40131637C68A86D17958E.description: Express ideas about family and neighborhood using paint.

F8334DE0DFE40131637B68A86D17958E.description: Expression Through Original Works of Art

F832D630DFE40131637A68A86D17958E.description: Create three-dimensional constructions using basic tools and art processes, such as paper and foam products, scissors, and glue.

F8327540DFE40131637968A86D17958E.description: Create symmetrical, patterned and random arrangements using lines, shapes, forms, and colors.

F83210F0DFE40131637868A86D17958E.description: Use basic geometric shapes to create an image of a person

F831AC20DFE40131637768A86D17958E.description: Assemble a collage with cut or torn paper shapes.

F830D560DFE40131637568A86D17958E.description: Apply artistic processes and skills in a variety of media to communicate meaning and intent in original works of art. (Production and Creative Expression)

F83074A0DFE40131637468A86D17958E.description: Recognize and describe simple patterns found in the environment and works of art

F8300EA0DFE40131637368A86D17958E.description: Identify and name the elements of art (line, color, shape, and texture - sight/touch, rough/smooth) in objects in nature, in the environment, and in works of art. Examples such as Klee's Way to the Chapel, Bonnard's Open Window, and Hopper's Approaching a City can be viewed at The Phillips Collection. Other works can be seen at the Corcoran Gallery of Art.
